<subSubSection pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Not uncommon in South Africa.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Foerster, 1869" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Alloxysta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alloxysta</taxonomicName>
, but usually with a habitus more resembling other figitids. Easily recognised among charipines through the possession of a mesopleural carina.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<paragraph pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Figure 16. 
<taxonomicName authority="Förster, 1869" authorityName="Förster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Phaenoglyphis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phaenoglyphis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phaenoglyphis</taxonomicName>
species (South Africa). A habitus lateral view B head and mesosoma dorso-lateral view C pronotum, dorso-anterior view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Worldwide, but most abundant in Holarctic. Afrotropical records: South Africa (
<bibRefCitation author="Gaston, KJ" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Royal Society B, Biological Sciences" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="1091 - 1098" title="Rates of species introduction to a remote oceanic island." volume="270" year="2003">Gaston et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
). Seemingly introduced.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<pageBreakToken pageId="47" pageNumber="48" start="start">Biology</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
Hyperparasitoids attacking aphelinid and aphidiine wasps on aphids (
<bibRefCitation author="Kierych, E" journalOrPublisher="Annales Zoologici" pageId="153" pageNumber="154" pagination="453 - 460" title="Notes on the genera Dilyta Foerster, 1869, and Glyptoxysta Thomson, 1877 (Hymenoptera, Cynipoidea, Alloxystidae) part 1." volume="34" year="1979">Kierych 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Quinlan, J" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="158" pageNumber="159" pagination="427 - 430" title="Status of the subfamily names Charipinae and Alloxystinae (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae)." url="10.1111/j.1365-3113.1980.tb00426.x" volume="5" year="1980">Quinlan and Evenhuis 1980</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Fergusson, NDM" journalOrPublisher="London" pageId="151" pageNumber="152" pagination="1 - 55" title="Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects" year="1986">Fergusson 1986</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="species richness">
<paragraph pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Species richness.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName authority="Förster, 1869" authorityName="Förster" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Phaenoglyphis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phaenoglyphis villosa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="villosa">Phaenoglyphis villosa</taxonomicName>
(Hartig, 1841) (
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xystus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xystus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Xystus</taxonomicName>
) (South Africa; this species is widespread throughout the world (Pujade-Villar et al. 2007)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
